node.text:
Male chimps who form strong bonds with other males in their troop are more likely to father offspring, a new study finds. There are two paths to doing this, either getting in close with the most powerful figures, or developing a large network of less dominant friends. The findings not only discredit some simplistic models of animal, and human, mating dynamics, they also shed light on the forces that allow social primates to flourish.

Animal sex lives are often portrayed as a world of pure competition, where males fight for access to females, and only the strongest or trickiest succeed. There are plenty of alternative examples, however, at least in social animals, now including our nearest relatives.
​
​​For the full story hit this image post via the link in our bio. 📖

Pompeii mummy discovered!
​
​This finding, by the Archaeological Park of Pompeii and the European University of Valencia, is very unusual as it was customary at the time to bury children and cremate adults. The burial chamber includes a marble slab with the name Marcus Venerius Secundio, believed to be the identity of the body found. Analysis of the bones suggests he was over 60 years old.

The mummified remains are in an incredible state of preservation, with hair and an ear still visible.
​
For the full story hit this image post via the link in our bio. 📖
​
​Image credit: Scheletro Porta Sarno

node.text:
This #UnderwaterWednesday we’re taking a closer look at the teeth of one of the ocean’s greatest hunters: sharks. Their teeth come in a remarkable diversity of shapes and sizes, and being the greatest tool in their arsenal means they need to keep them sharp.

One way in which sharks achieve this is by having multiple rows of teeth, with some having as many as 15 rows of teeth in each jaw. You can see a similar set up in these photos of a dogfish shark. The teeth are constantly being lost and replaced, turning over like a conveyor belt of spikey death triangles. 

While these teeth might look a bit intimidating, dogfish pose no risk to humans at the bitey end, but some have sharp spines that can cause damage if you mishandle them. Takeaway: please don’t pet the sea pupper.
​
​Image courtesy of: @huwiceandstuff

node.text:
The jaguar (Panthera onca) is the third biggest cat in the world (after the tiger and the lion) and can grow up to 170cm (5.6 ft) long, not including their tails which add an extra 80cm (2.6 ft)! Jaguars have the strongest bite of any large cat, with which they sink their teeth into crocodilians' thick hides and turtles' sturdy shells. Jaguars are also able to bite right through the skulls of mammalian prey, delivering a lethal blow as they slurp up the brain. Nom nom!

Jaguars used to be found from the south-west USA and throughout South America, but they've now been nearly eradicated from half of their historical range. Brazil is the jaguars' stronghold, with an estimated 170,000 wild jaguars living there.

The population of jaguars has plummeted due to poaching and high deforestation rates in South America for both logging and clearing space for cattle ranching.

node.text:
This image of a spectacular stellar nursery within the constellation of Gemini was captured by the Hubble Space Telescope. Named AFGL 5180, it was snapped in both visible and infrared light. A massive star is forming near the center, and powerful jets of gas are blasting holes through the clouds of dust, stretching to the corners of the image. ESA gave a particularly poetic description of the scene, explaining: “Light from this star is mostly escaping and reaching us by illuminating these cavities, like a lighthouse piercing through the storm clouds.”
​ 
Credit: ESA/Hubble & NASA, J. C. Tan (Chalmers University & University of Virginia), R. Fedriani (Chalmers University); Acknowledgment: Judy Schmidt

The winners of the Nikon Small World In Motion video competition have been announced, and we’ll be sharing some with you over the next couple of days.
​
This year’s first prize was awarded to Fabian J. Weston for a video showing the symbiotic relationship between termites and microscopic microfauna.
​
Fabian used a research microscope from the 1970s, along with polarized light to produce a visually stunning video of live microfauna in the gut of a termite.
​ 
Now celebrating its 11th year, Nikon Small World in Motion is the video component of the long-standing Nikon Small World still-photography competition. The competition recognizes proficiency and excellence of photography and video taken under the microscope.
​ 
Video credit: Fabian J. Weston / Pennant Hills, New South Wales, Australia
Courtesy of Nikon Small World In Motion @nikoninstruments

BepiColombo, a joint ESA-Japanese Space Agency Mission (JAXA) flew past the planet Venus on Tuesday, August 10 at 552 kilometers (340 miles) away. It took its pictures as it moved past Venus, showing the planet receding further and further from view. The probe will be able to continue its photographing and taking measurements until August 18. This footage here is made from 89 images taken by the spacecraft and stitched together by the team.

Happy #MicrobeMonday! Today we’re bringing you a wonderful little tardigrade. We’ve posted about these little water bears many times in the past, but did you know they have four to six claws on each foot to help them cling to plant matter? They also have a needle-like mouth part that can extend and pierce plant cells to drink up its delicious cytoplasm. Yum!
​ 
Video courtesy of @jam_and_germs

The BMC Ecology and Evolution Image Competition winners have been announced, with this stunning photograph depicting a school of jack fish in a spiral formation taken by Kristen Brown from the University of Pennsylvania being crowned the overall winner.

Kristen Brown said: “This image represents both the beauty and bounty of our oceans as well as the spiralling crisis unfolding within the marine environment.”

The photo competition was created by the Springer Nature journal and BMC to give ecologists and evolutionary biologists the opportunity to use their creativity to highlight their work and celebrate the intersection between art and science.
​ 
Image Credit: Kristen Brown

Here kitty kitty! The Bengal cat is a mix of domestic cats, particularly the spotted Egyptian Mau, and the Asian leopard cat. Their golden sheen derives from their leopard cat ancestors, which have spots and arrowhead patterns on their fur.

As wild as their appearance sounds, their personality greatly reflects that, with the Bengal cat being a naturally energetic breed that needs their play and exercise. They can also naturally retrieve items and enjoy playing in water, as seen here with this kitty playing by the seashore. Aww!

Image credit: Jevgenija ZUK / Shutterstock
